,"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe urinary bladder has multiple innate defence mechanisms to prevent infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EMannosylated proteins\u003C/strong\u003E on the uroepithelium act as decoy receptors that bind to bacterial adhesins, preventing bacterial attachment to the bladder wall. This is distinct from adaptive immune responses like \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmunoglobulin A\u003C/strong\u003E production, \u003Cstrong\u003ET-lymphocyte\u003C/strong\u003E recruitment, \u003Cstrong\u003Ememory B-cell\u003C/strong\u003E activation, or \u003Cstrong\u003Eneutrophil\u003C/strong\u003E chemotaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important innate defence mechanisms include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERegular bladder emptying and urine flow that mechanically removes bacteria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAcidic urinary pH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAntimicrobial peptides in the urine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe glycosaminoglycan layer that forms a protective barrier on the bladder epithelium\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The bladder has multiple innate defence mechanisms including mannosylated proteins that prevent bacterial adhesion","Urine flow, acidic pH, and antimicrobial peptides help protect against urinary tract infections","The glycosaminoglycan layer forms a protective barrier on bladder epithelium"],"references":["Hickling DR, Sun TT, Wu XR. Anatomy and Physiology of the Urinary Tract: Relation to Host Defense and Microbial Infection. Microbiol Spectr. 2015 Aug;3(4):10.1128/microbiolspec.UTI-0016-2012. doi: 10.1128/microbiolspec.UTI-0016-2012. PMID: 26350322; PMCID: PMC4566164.","Khandelwal P, Abraham SN, Apodaca G. Cell biology and physiology of the uroepithelium. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 2009 Dec;297(6):F1477-501. doi: 10.1152/ajprenal.00327.2009. Epub 2009 Jul 8. PMID: 19587142; PMCID: PMC2801337.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. 